<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Home Office Response</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written Evidence from the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Home Office [CST0021]</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Thank you for your invitation to submit evidence to the Committee's inquiry into crime statistics</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I am replying as the Chief Statistician and Head of Profession for Statistics in the Home Office on behalf of my teams and our colleagues. The Committee has asked six specific questions about crime statistics. These questions and your inquiry are focused on police recorded crime statistics. We believe it is for the police service, Her Majesty’s Inspectorate of Constabulary and the Office of National Statistics to additionally give their opinions on much of what you ask. Attached is the Home Office response to those questions.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We believe it is very important to highlight that crime statistics are not based on police recorded crime alone. Rather they are formed by gathering together that police data and presenting it alongside the results from the Crime Survey of England and Wales (formerly the British Crime Survey).  The survey reflects the experiences of victims, regardless of whether they have reported crimes to the police. As a result we do not rely on one source in isolation with policy makers using them in conjunction. It is only by using the two sources alongside each other that their true value can be unlocked.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 13.35pt; padding-left:15pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Home Office has been collecting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">data</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">from the police </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">number </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">recorded</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> crimes since </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the nineteenth century</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. This has been based </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> counts of the number of specific offences </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">set out </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the notifiable offence list (NOL). </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Since the mid 1990s t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">his list includes all indictable </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">only </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">crimes (i.e. those tried </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">only </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">at Crown Court) and all those that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">heard</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> either at a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rown court or a magistrate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s court</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (either way offences) together with a s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mall number of summary only offences included to provide completeness</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 13.35pt; padding-left:15pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We consider</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that focussing on police recorded crime in isolation is not always helpful as crime statistics overall are drawn from the two complementary sources – recorded crime and the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> results from the Crime Survey of England and Wales (CSEW – previously the British Crime Survey).  Whilst each source has its own strengths (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for example, recorded crime is the only source of information on some crimes such as drug trafficking and homicide</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">while the crime survey is the best source for long</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">er</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> term trends</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">) taken together they present a fuller and more rounded set of statistics that can be better </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">relied upon by users</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Any application</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of crime statistics </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">which focuses too heavily on one source or the other </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">may not reach the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">most accurate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> conclusion.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:15pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Police recording practice is governed by the Home Office Counting Rules (HOCR) and the National Crime Recording Standard (NCRS). </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The HOCR have been in place fo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r many years </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">but</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">current form</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> they date back to the mid 1990s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">when the last major change to the offences included in police recorded crime w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> made.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">These rules s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">et</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> out whether, how and when to record a crime. They are designed to provide a consi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">stent approach across force</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s as to how they </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">record and classify offences.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  The HOCR are reviewed regularly to ensure they remain fit for purpose</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">support </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">transparen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and reflect changes in the law.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  They are published at: </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/counting-rules-for-recorded-crime"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/counting-rules-for-recorded-crime</span></a></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 13.35pt; padding-left:15pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The NCRS was introduced in 2002 to better underpin the HOCR following an earlier review by HMIC which found some wide v</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ariation in recording practice</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> across forces. NCRS </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sets out that recording by the police is victim focussed and that all reports of crimes should be recorded unless there is credible evidence available at the time of the report to show that the crime did </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">not happen. This was a significant change </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">meaning </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">recorded crime statistics</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> prior to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2002 cannot be reliably compared with those from before that time</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:15pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The HOCR, supported by the NCRS, directs that the police should create an incident record for every repo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rt made to them irrespective of the source of that report. Once the police have made an initial assessment of each such incident report then the rules set out that  a crime must be recorded in each case where </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the circumstances as reported amount to a crim</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e defined by law and there is no </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">immediate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">credible evidence to the contrary. Once recorded, a crime </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">can subsequently be cancelled (known as “no crimed”) if</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> additional verifiable information </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">becomes available that determines that the crime did not happen.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Rules around no crimes are set out in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the HOCR</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:15pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">At the same time that NCRS was introduced the Home Office put in place a regular programme of external auditing by the Audit Commission. These reviews ran over a period of four years from 2003/4 to 2006/7 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and examined each force’s compliance with the HOCR and the accuracy of their recorded crime data.  Whilst there was some initial variation these audits showed consistent improvement in compliance with all forces achieving a standard </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">deemed acceptable by th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e Audit Commission </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by the time of the final review.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Responsibility for on-going </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">inspection </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of police crime recording now rests with HMIC.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:15pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Alongside </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">these external reviews forces were provided with guidance on their own</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> internal audit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">crime records </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nsure </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">compliance with the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">required standards</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The NCRS included </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the establishment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a Force Crime Registrar </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(FCR) in each force </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">whose role it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ensure that the requirements of the NCRS are maintained and to ensure greater consistency across forces. In</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> particular the FCR is there to act as a final arbiter for the audit process, for interpretation of the counting rules and to act as a single point of contact with the Home Office (and other stakeholders) on all matters relating to the crime recording proc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ess. The Home Office also has an established civil servant (with the relevant knowledge and experience ) in the role of National</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rime Registrar </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(NCR) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">who has day to day ownership of t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he HOCR, advises FCRs and others</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">such as HMIC inspectors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and members of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the new independent crime statistics advisory committee</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on questions and issues relating to police crime recording. The NCR operates a wide ranging framework of strategic and technical working groups </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that consider proposals for change to the HOCR, issue </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">new guidance on recording and support</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">quality assure </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">work. Part of the remit of those groups is to maintain and update a data quality assurance manual to guide practitioners in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">forces.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:15pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Whilst publication of police recorded crime statistics has shifted to the ONS the Home </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ffice retains the responsibility for ownership and oversight of the HOCR and for the initial collection and quality assurance of the data.  Only once Home </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ffice statis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ticians are satisfied with it is the data passed onto ONS. The Home Office statistics unit carry out a range of checks to highlight apparent inconsistencies and where ident</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">fied these are referred back to forces for clarification prior to publication. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:15pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Cri</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">me recording for statistical purposes presents some burden on the police and we are clear that those burdens must be limited to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">those that are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">necessary and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">proportionate. The amount of time and effort that is consumed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">must be balanced </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">between the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> needs of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> victims and of users of the statistics</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">must also be risk based and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">take account of the burden it creates.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The committee has asked the following specific questions and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">our</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> responses are shown below.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Are crimes being recorded by the police when they s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">hould be? Are crimes being categorised correctly? </span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:9.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As outlined above The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Home Office Counting Rules (HOCR) and National Crime Recording Standard (NCRS) provide the police with appropriate and robust rules within which crimes should be recorded and categori</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sed.  The former also provides examples of how to classify certain crimes, for example guiding officers when there may be uncertainty between a theft and a burglary.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> A number of reviews (including those by HMIC, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">N</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ational </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Statistician</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and others) have all conclude</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that both the HOCR and NCRS remain fit for purpose and appropriate for the use to which they are put.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:9.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Each</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">force</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has a Crime</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Registrar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (FCR)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">who acts as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">final arbiter for crime recording in the force.  As well as providing g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uidance on individual queries, they oversee the bulk of crime </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">recording in the force and can highlight </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">anomalies in crime recording.   </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We make clear that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the FCR</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should be outside the operational line </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">command and be able to report directly to the senior</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> officer responsible for the accuracy and integrity of crime recording and data. We expect HMIC to include an assessment of the independence of the FCR in their force inspections. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The National Crime Registrar sits within the Home Office Crime Statistics te</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">am and is responsible for maintaining and developing the counting rules and overseeing the recording of crime nationally, working with F</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CRs and others. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:9.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">MIC have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">carried out periodic </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">audits</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and inspections on crime recording and are about to commence an a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ll force in depth inspection scheduled to provide an interim report in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">spring</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of 2014. It is for HMIC to provide greater detail and context on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">their</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> plan. Home </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ffice </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ministers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> have been very clear that such inspection work is undertaken. For example, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in her letter to HMIC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">agreeing to their programme of inspections</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the Home </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Secretary</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> said “it is vital that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the public have access to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">transparent and trustworthy statistics on recorded crime”</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:9.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As outlined above a rolling programme of annual audits was undertaken by the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">udit </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ommission over a number or years. These audits showed continuing improvements with all forces reaching a good standard of compliance in the final year they reported. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">At tha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t time the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ommission considered 90% overall compliance to be good. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Subsequently HMIC have conducted periodic work and continue to do so. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Where such reviews have highlighted specific concerns forces have acted on them.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:9.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Monthly crime maps, available on poli</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ce.uk present timely crime figures in local areas.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Police and Crime Commissioners now have a role in improving transparency and accuracy of data and if</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> users feel that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">crimes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are not being recorded correctly, they can </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">now </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">challenge their force </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">through the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ir </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">PCC.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What are the factors which can influence police mis-recording of crime?</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:9.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The HOCR and their related guidance are extensive and there may be occasions where they could be subject of mis-interpretation. The role of the FCR in each force and the cent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ral oversight of the NCR and related processes seek to ensure that such mis-interpretation is both identified and resolved. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:9.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Pressure to meet targets can promote inappropriat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e behaviour and influence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> mis-clas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sification</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> For example there may be pressures w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ithin forces, through PCCs or by ACPO to reduce crime relative to neighbouring forces.  Equally</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> individual targets for each officer may be linked to the number of offenders identified and against whom action is taken</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and these may also drive perverse inc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">entives. However the Home Office sets no such targets and all previous targets were scrapped by the Home Secretary to remove those incentives.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:9.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the past it was argued by some that the measures </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of “sanction</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> detections</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">” and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the targets linked to them res</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ulted in some skewing of crime figures whilst forces chased the targets seeking to gain easy detections</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> or as a result of some in forces seeking to find ways to avoid recording crimes where they perceived it would prove impossible to achieve a detection. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> To help to ensure that this </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">perceived </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">incentive  is removed the Home Office has now abolished the regime of sanction detections and replaced them with a framework of crime outcomes which will, in 2014, be extended to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">improve transparency of crime recordin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">g by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">provid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> an outcome for all recorded crimes.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Are the right checks in place to ensure that the systems for recording crime function effectively and accurately? </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:9.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The HOCR and NCRS </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lay down </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a clear set of rules which provide a high level of consistency in the recording of crime within and between forces and over time.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As previously mentioned the role of FCR exists in each force to underpin consistency and application of those rules.  The Hom</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Office </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">actively supports the role of FCR whilst recognising that in the current financial climate there are inevitable pressures on them. Nonetheless we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">know that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> having an objective FCR with appropriate influence and support </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> chief officers </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">underpins</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">good recording decision</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> making</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in forces. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">HMIC commented</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in 2012 that in some forces the FCR may not be sufficiently independent of those responsible for delivering performance improvements.  The Home Office, working with the national policing lead and HMI</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> ha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> sent clear guidance that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">where </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">we believe this is the case then change</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> should be made.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:9.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As outlined in the introduction there was a programme of regular annual audit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for a number of years. These audits evidenced improvements with all forces </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">achievi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ng levels</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of compliance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> deemed good at that time</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  HMIC now undertake inspections and as stated are planning a wide ranging review of crime data integrity in the coming year. At the same time crime recording also features as a part of other thematic inspec</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tions. The Home Secretary in her letter to HMIC agreeing their programme of work for 2013/14 also commented that “ it is clearly critical a report on crime data integrity is published during the year”</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:9.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We wish to see this work by HMIC become a regular featu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">re of their work programme </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">whilst</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> recognising that inspection itself creates burdens on the police. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> To that end inspections will need to be risk based and focussed on areas of concern building on previous work.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:9.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">With the advent of Police and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rime Commiss</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ioners there is now another key player with an interest in and responsibility for the accuracy and integrity of crime data. The public </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">must</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> have trustworthy statistics with which to hold </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">their</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> force</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> through their PCC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to account. PCCs in turn will wish to assure themselves that the data they rely on is of sufficient quality. As was seen recently in Kent a PCC can directly commission HMIC to conduct inspection activity on crime recording. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Whilst that report found room </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for improvement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> early indications are that the range of changes subsequently introduced in that force are showing positive results.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:9.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To allow forces</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, PCCs and HMIC to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> better assess</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and assure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the data the Home Office maintains an on-line tool (Iquanta) wi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">th monthly management information allowing comparisons to be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">made</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> both over time and against similar or neighbouring areas.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:9.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Home Office is also developing a national data hub to allow forces to submit record </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">level</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> crime data directly removing previous</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> more burdensome manually based returns and also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">giving a greater level of detail which in turn allows Home </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ffice statisticians to better quality assure the data before it is published as part of the national statistics outputs.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-si