11pt"> and policing statistics. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:9.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ecommendations </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">from</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> those reviews have been acted on. For example as already mentioned the Home Secretary agreed in 2011 to move the responsibility for publication of crime statistics away from the Home office to the ONS and agreed to the establishment of an independent Crim</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e Statistics Advisory committee made up of a range of members</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> including academics working in criminology and statistics</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> who now provide advice to Ministers, ONS and HMIC on any changes proposed that would affect the resulting data and on means by which t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rust and transparency might be further improved. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This includes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> advising HMIC on the methodology they employ to assess and comment on police crime recording.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:9.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Home Office has also established a National Crime Recording Strategic Steering Group (building</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on work conducted by a previous steering group but with much greater strategic focus)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with representation from all stakeholders including the Police and HMIC which will scrutinise all proposals for change and take forward issues raised where it may be sug</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gested that the existing rules or practices are either not operating effectively or can be strengthened to ensure that all crimes are recorded where they should be. This group will also focus on the burdens that crime recording can present to seek to minim</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ise the impact these processes may have. The Steering Group will have oversight of the various standing and ad hoc working groups that are in place to support FCRs and other crime recording practitioners in interpreting the rules, providing guidance and su</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pporting proportionate and risk based internal QA.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:9.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Home Office (working with the Police service) have made available the crime maps on the police.uk website and we continue to make further improvements </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(such as including outcomes) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to them and add to t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">heir functionality and the range of data they include.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:9.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Home </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ffice has recognised that the CSEW (crime survey) does not include crimes against business and in recognition of this has established an additional commercial victimisation survey to capture</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the crimes experienced by the business community. The first publication of the results</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of this new survey was made </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">January 2013</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">To what extent can policy-makers have confidence in the statistics which result from the recording of crime by police forc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">es?</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:9.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The ONS have commented (most recently in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">October</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 2013) that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">system of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">recording crime by the Police is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">widely recognised to be one of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the best in the world. It is worthy of note that the NCRS has been used a template in other jurisdictions across the globe </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">including</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in Australia where it exists largely unchanged from the version in play in this country. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:9.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mentioned </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">above crime statist</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ics are not comprised </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">solely</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of police recorded data but also of the results from the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Crime Survey for England and Wales</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  It is rare for policy makers to have two such robust </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">complementary indicators from different </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sources on which to draw conclusions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ese</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> two sources complement each other and pre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sent policy makers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with a wider </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">range</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of dat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a on which to base their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">decision making.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Both the police recorded crime series and the crime survey have shown similar trends in recent years (albeit with some diverg</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ence between 2007/8-2011/12).  Each measure has strengths so policy makers use them in conjunction.  We do not rely solely on one measure.  However, the police recorded crime series is the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">only</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> reliable source of information for some crime types.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:9.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We acce</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pt that, given crime statistics can be used as a key indicator of police performance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> confidence is absolutely paramount and this is why we welcome HMICs reviews and emphasis on this work.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Should recorded crime statistics be classified as national </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">statistics?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:9.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Ultimately this is a question for the UK Statistics Authority assessment team however the statistics have passed assessment and police recorded crime statistics continue to be produced in accordance with the code of practice by professional st</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">atisticians in both the Home </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ffice and the ONS.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:9.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The ONS have commented that the recording of crime for statistical purposes by the police is amongst the best in the world and we have seen no evidence to call into question the classification of th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ese</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> data</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as national statistics.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Helv; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>